<HEADLINE>
<P>
SOCCER; U.S. TO TEST PROGRESS AGAINST TOP CHILEAN SQUAD 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By GRAHAME L. JONES 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The United States plays Chile today in a soccer "friendly" at University 
Stadium in Albuquerque, N.M. 
</P>
<P>
 Coach Bora Milutinovic has taken an 18-member team to the University of New 
Mexico, choosing to leave behind defender Jeff Agoos, midfielder Brian Quinn 
and forward Joe-Max Moore. Moore is recovering from injury, but the absence of 
Agoos and Quinn was not explained.Forward Peter Vermes was cut this week. 
</P>
<P>
 Chile, which was barred from competing in the 1994 World Cup because it 
cheated by feigning injury and walking off the field during a qualifying match 
against Brazil for the 1990 tournament, has brought a strong team to the United 
States. 
</P>
<P>
 The Chileans' 16-man roster includes 10 players who were on Chile's Copa 
America, or South American Championship, squad in Ecuador last year. However, 
Chile's most dangerous player, striker Ivan Zamorano, could not gain release to 
play in the match from his Spanish club team, Real Madrid. GRAHAME L. JONES 
</P>
